Comparative Study of Adversarial Generative Models on CIFAR-10: From Conditional WGANs to Self-Attention GANs

Group Information

  • Group ID: ADL Group 75
  • Group Members:
    1. Ravindra Kumar Tholiya - 2023AA05124
    2. Shivam Sahil - 2023AA05663
    3. Jahnavi Gali - 2023AA05684
    4. Chakshu - 2023AA05280

Summary of Observations - Task 1 cWGAN

  • Highest Inception Score (~3.63.7), but relatively high FID (~110115).
  • Interpretation: The generated images were diver enough that the classifier recognized multiple classes (yielding a higher IS),
  • But they werent particularly close to real images in distribution (leading to the higher FID).

Summary of Observations - Task 2 SNGAN

Slightly lower Inception Score (IS) than cWGAN:

  • Indicates somewhat less class diversity in the generated samples.
  • The model may lean toward producing images from certain modes of the CIFAR-10 distribution more frequently.

Significantly better Frchet Inception Distance (FID) compared to cWGAN:

  • Suggests the generated images are closer to the real data distribution overall.
  • Visual inspection often shows more coherent structures, fewer artifacts, and better color consistency.

Role of Spectral Normalization:

  • Helps stabilize training by constraining the discriminators capacity, preventing it from overpowering the generator.
  • Likely responsible for the smoother convergence and more realistic image details.

Training Observations:

  • The logs show steady, incremental improvements; no signs of severe mode collapse.
  • Consistent generator and discriminator losses suggest balanced adversarial updates.

Overall Takeaway:

  • SNGAN trades off a bit of image diversity (hence a slightly lower IS) for more accurate alignment with real image features (manifested in the lower FID).
  • Highlights how spectral normalization can improve visual fidelity while modestly restricting the range of generated variations.

Summary of Observations - Task 3 SAGAN variant without spectral norm and TTUB

Inception Score

Inception Score is quite low (1.7), indicating very limited diversity and poor generation quality.

  • Many generated samples appear visually similar or fail to convincingly match any specific CIFAR-10 class.

FID above 300 underscores significant divergence from the real data distribution.

  • Images likely contain noticeable artifacts or structural inconsistencies.

Role of Removing Spectral Normalization:

  • Without spectral normalization, the discriminator can become overly strong or unstable, leading to erratic adversarial feedback.
  • This often results in either mode collapse or chaotic generator outputs.

Self-Attention Alone Not Enough:

  • Although self-attention can capture long-range dependencies, stability mechanisms like spectral norm and TTUB are also crucial.
  • Simply adding attention without these controls can exacerbate training instability.

Training Observations:

  • Large, unpredictable swings in generator and discriminator losses suggest severe training volatility.
  • The model never fully converged to a stable solution despite extended epochs.

Overall Takeaway:

  • Partial SAGAN highlights that self-attention alone does not guarantee performance improvements.
  • Proper regularization (spectral norm, TTUB) and balanced hyperparameters are essential for stable high-fidelity generation.

Summary of Observations - Task 4 Full SAGAN with spectral norm + TTUB

Inception Score

Inception Score remains low (~1.61.7), despite reintroducing spectral normalization and TTUB.
  • Indicates the model is still failing to diversify or properly learn class characteristics in CIFAR-10.

High FID (300360 range):

  • Generated images deviate significantly from the real data manifold, suggesting unresolved training instability or suboptimal hyperparameters.

Spectral Normalization + TTUB:

  • These features are designed to stabilize the discriminator and improve gradient flow.
  • However, the poor results suggest other factors (e.g., learning rate, batch size, architecture details) may still be improperly tuned.

Self-Attention Implementation:

  • While attention can improve global coherence, it is computationally more demanding and finicky to train.
  • If the rest of the pipeline (optimizer settings, initialization) is not carefully managed, improvements from attention may be canceled out by instability.

Training Observations:

  • Logs show fluctuating losses, sometimes spiking generator losses followed by near-zero discriminator losses or vice versa.
  • The system never reaches the mode coverage or fidelity levels seen in simpler methods (cWGAN/SNGAN).

Overall Takeaway:

  • Full SAGAN potentially has the highest capacity but is also the most sensitive to training hyperparameters and architecture details.
  • Achieving the expected performance requires a more rigorous hyperparameter search, perhaps an alternate training schedule, or additional regularizations.

Training Behaviors & Instability

  • Tasks 1 & 2 (cWGAN & SNGAN) both seemed moderately stable:

    • No glaring Mode Collapse issues or exploding gradients in the logs.

      • Incremental improvements to IS and FID over epochs, although cWGANs FID stayed relatively high.
    • Tasks 3 & 4 (Both SAGAN variants) showed large generator losses, occasionally near-zero discriminator losses, or big swings:
      • These are typical signatures of instability in adversarial training.
      • The final results confirm that the networks didnt converge to a high-quality image distribution.
      • The attention mechanism plus or minus spectral normalization can be tricky to tune, and the resulting training was more erratic.

Hyperparameters & Implementation Details

  • While the cWGAN and SNGAN code/hyperparameters (batch size, learning rate schedules, etc.) seemed to stabilize training well enough for decent results, the SAGAN setups were likely more sensitive to parameter choices.
  • For instance, SAGAN often requires more careful balancing of learning rates, an appropriate beta1/beta2 for Adam/AdamW, and possibly a tuned batch size. If any of these were off or inconsistent, it could severely degrade performance (as seems to have happened in Tasks 3 & 4).

Key Takeaways

  • Conditional cWGAN can excel in generating class-distinguishable images (good IS) but might struggle with matching the fine-grained distribution (hence higher FID).
    • SNGAN remains a strong baseline, especially for overall fidelity and stability. Spectral normalization is quite effective at keeping the discriminator from overpowering the generator.
    • SAGAN (with self-attention) should improve performance if carefully tuned especially in capturing global features and finer details but in this particular setup, it underperformed. That underperformance likely reflects an issue in hyperparameters, code implementation, or training strategy rather than the SAGAN architecture itself.
    • Even small code details or hyperparameter changes can drastically affect training stability in attention-based GANs. The big leaps in generator/discriminator losses in the logs highlight how quickly things can break if not carefully balanced.

Enhancements

  • Re-verification and optimisation of learning rate policies, weight initialization, and optimizer settings for SAGAN variants.
  • Experiment with smaller steps of spectral norm or different attention-block placements.
  • Increasing training epochs or adding other regularization to see if SAGAN performance can catch up.

Conclusion

cWGAN gave us the strongest Inception Score, SNGAN gave us the best FID, and both SAGAN variants struggled significantly (likely due to hyperparameter or architectural issues).
This highlights just how sensitive GAN training can be especially once we add more sophisticated modules like self-attention.
